              "text": "Unit tests are a type of software testing where individual, isolated components of code—typically single functions or methods—are verified for correctness. Developers write these tests to ensure that a specific unit of logic produces the expected output for a given set of inputs. They are highly useful because they act as a safety net, allowing programmers to refactor or update code with the confidence that they haven't broken existing functionality. By catching bugs early in the development cycle, unit tests significantly reduce the time and cost associated with fixing defects later. Additionally, they serve as a form of living documentation, demonstrating exactly how a piece of code is intended to be used. Ultimately, a robust suite of unit tests leads to more maintainable, reliable, and higher-quality software.",
